Hello folks, I found a solution because I personally found the fact that typeorm does not offer bit(1) as a boolean in MySQL, found another solution!
TypeORM has a Raw() function, or the In() function.

However, the BoolBitTransformer must be changed for this.

```typescript
import {FindOperator, ValueTransformer} from 'typeorm';

export class BoolBitTransformer implements ValueTransformer {
    // To db from typeorm
    to(value: boolean | null): Buffer | null {
        if ((value as any) instanceof FindOperator) {
            return <any>value;
        }
        if (value === null) {
            return null;
        }
        const res = Buffer.alloc(1);
        res[0] = value ? 1 : 0;
        return res;
    }

    // From db to typeorm
    from(value: Buffer): boolean | null {
        if (value === null) {
            return null;
        }
        return value[0] === 1;
    }
}
```

And if you now want to search for true or false, you have to specify this in the query.

Raw() Function:
```typescript
const boolean: boolean = true; // true, false
const data = await Staff.find({
    where: {
        active: boolean ? Raw('true') : Raw('false') 
    }
});
```

In() Function:
```typescript
const boolean: boolean = true; // true, false, null
const data = await Staff.find({
    where: {
        active: In([boolean])
    }
});
```


Personally, I prefer the In() function because you can also pass true, false and null here, even as a variable without any problems.

So I'll go and rewrite my code, I hope I could make life easier for others (:

